1
00:00:00,348 --> 00:00:05,793
AI DevKit is an operating model for AI-centric software engineering.

2
00:00:06,134 --> 00:00:08,952
AI writes specs, tests,

3
00:00:09,032 --> 00:00:10,313
code, and docs.

4
00:00:11,535 --> 00:00:14,234
Humans approve the spec and approve the release.

5
00:00:14,913 --> 00:00:18,149
It works with your existing stack — git,

6
00:00:18,283 --> 00:00:24,786
repos, pull requests, CI — and reshapes it around AI execution,

7
00:00:24,801 --> 00:00:27,341
while keeping the human checkpoints that matter.

8
00:00:29,248 --> 00:00:32,017
There are four pillars: spec planning,

9
00:00:32,104 --> 00:00:37,570
test-driven implementation, Progressive Disclosure docs, and the AI

10
00:00:37,670 --> 00:00:38,935
dev environment.

11
00:00:38,935 --> 00:00:40,850
Work comes in as a story,

12
00:00:40,929 --> 00:00:42,609
epic, bug, or feature.

13
00:00:43,409 --> 00:00:46,521
It flows through three phases:

14
00:00:46,600 --> 00:00:49,396
Plan, Implementation, and Release.

15
00:00:51,295 --> 00:00:53,634
The Lead AI executes the workflow.

16
00:00:54,394 --> 00:00:59,546
The Verifier AI independently checks key transitions — it's

17
00:00:59,587 --> 00:01:02,502
a second AI from a different training lineage.

18
00:01:04,486 --> 00:01:05,623
Why two AIs?

19
00:01:06,224 --> 00:01:10,582
A single AI is confidently wrong in ways invisible to

20
00:01:10,663 --> 00:01:11,862
itself.

21
00:01:12,222 --> 00:01:15,938
Asking the same model to review its own output rarely

22
00:01:15,998 --> 00:01:16,975
catches the error.

23
00:01:18,795 --> 00:01:22,454
Two independent lineages catch different mistakes.

24
00:01:23,519 --> 00:01:25,371
The Plan phase produces a spec.

25
00:01:26,091 --> 00:01:30,334
The Implementation phase produces working code,

26
00:01:30,441 --> 00:01:32,575
tests, and updated docs.

27
00:01:33,336 --> 00:01:38,498
That deliverable passes through Release — a CI gate plus

28
00:01:38,564 --> 00:01:39,537
human approval.

29
00:01:39,537 --> 00:01:45,695
Plan turns a work item into an approved spec.

30
00:01:47,034 --> 00:01:49,860
The Lead AI reads the requirement,

31
00:01:49,900 --> 00:01:54,425
the docs, and the code, then drafts a spec with

32
00:01:54,475 --> 00:01:58,505
acceptance criteria, edge cases, and approach decisions.

33
00:02:01,044 --> 00:02:05,862
The Verifier AI reviews the spec independently.

34
00:02:06,701 --> 00:02:11,465
If the two AIs disagree on what a criterion means,

35
00:02:11,745 --> 00:02:15,465
that's ambiguity — and it gets surfaced to the human

36
00:02:15,545 --> 00:02:17,385
before any code is written.

37
00:02:19,294 --> 00:02:22,977
The key discipline here: decide in the spec,

38
00:02:23,076 --> 00:02:24,176
not in the code.

39
00:02:25,597 --> 00:02:28,968
If you let the AI defer decisions to implementation,

40
00:02:29,249 --> 00:02:31,610
it makes them implicitly,

41
00:02:31,689 --> 00:02:35,852
often inconsistently, and you only find out when you're reading

42
00:02:35,891 --> 00:02:36,652
the code.

43
00:02:38,831 --> 00:02:41,610
The phase ends when the human signs off.

44
00:02:41,610 --> 00:02:47,291
Implementation turns the approved spec into working code.

45
00:02:48,630 --> 00:02:53,289
The Verifier AI authors the failing tests directly from the spec.

46
00:02:54,329 --> 00:03:00,492
The Lead AI writes the implementation to make them pass.

47
00:03:02,538 --> 00:03:07,853
This is independent test authorship — the AI that writes the tests

48
00:03:08,013 --> 00:03:10,494
is not the AI that writes the code.

49
00:03:12,454 --> 00:03:17,685
Without that separation, implementation assumptions get silently baked

50
00:03:17,749 --> 00:03:20,647
into the tests.

51
00:03:22,260 --> 00:03:28,607
After TDD completes, the Lead AI updates the Progressive Disclosure docs,

52
00:03:29,067 --> 00:03:33,366
and the Verifier AI checks the updates against the actual

53
00:03:33,462 --> 00:03:33,926
code.

54
00:03:35,189 --> 00:03:38,487
Then the spec is archived.

55
00:03:39,248 --> 00:03:42,641
The docs carry everything forward.

56
00:03:42,641 --> 00:03:47,123
Progressive Disclosure docs give every repo the same structure.

57
00:03:49,192 --> 00:03:52,158
The same eight files, in every repo,

58
00:03:52,262 --> 00:03:54,723
across the whole organisation.

59
00:03:56,817 --> 00:04:01,120
Level zero is an identity card — what is this repo?

60
00:04:02,079 --> 00:04:06,484
Level one is eight fixed files:

61
00:04:06,884 --> 00:04:11,531
setup, architecture, code map,

62
00:04:11,604 --> 00:04:17,610
conventions, workflows, interfaces, gotchas,

63
00:04:17,730 --> 00:04:19,211
and security.

64
00:04:21,704 --> 00:04:26,971
Level two is deep dives, loaded only when level one isn't

65
00:04:27,005 --> 00:04:27,449
enough.

66
00:04:29,416 --> 00:04:33,689
Levels zero and one load upfront — they're small.

67
00:04:34,409 --> 00:04:38,413
Level two is pulled in only when needed.

68
00:04:39,173 --> 00:04:44,574
The agent gets full context without filling the context window.

69
00:04:46,641 --> 00:04:51,456
That consistency is what lets any agent pick up any repo and

70
00:04:51,536 --> 00:04:52,495
work safely.

71
00:04:54,314 --> 00:04:58,411
You can generate these docs for an existing repo today — that's

72
00:04:58,430 --> 00:05:00,089
the fastest way to start.

73
00:05:00,229 --> 00:05:04,253
Why prompts instead of skills or slash commands?

74
00:05:04,933 --> 00:05:07,293
Skills are tool-specific.

75
00:05:07,813 --> 00:05:11,048
A Claude Code skill doesn't work in Cursor.

76
00:05:11,607 --> 00:05:15,924
A Cursor command doesn't work in Codex.

77
00:05:16,740 --> 00:05:20,404
Prompts are portable — they work in any agent that can read

78
00:05:20,524 --> 00:05:21,604
files.

79
00:05:21,844 --> 00:05:24,646
The same prompt works in Claude Code,

80
00:05:24,783 --> 00:05:30,242
Cursor, Codex, Gemini, or whatever comes next.

81
00:05:31,792 --> 00:05:34,801
A prompt is visible text — you can read it,

82
00:05:34,859 --> 00:05:39,559
understand it, modify it, version-control it.

83
00:05:40,296 --> 00:05:44,312
When a workflow changes, you update the markdown file,

84
00:05:44,352 --> 00:05:47,826
and every prompt that references it picks up the change.

85
00:05:49,327 --> 00:05:51,743
If your tool supports custom commands,

86
00:05:52,024 --> 00:05:55,025
you can wrap the prompt for faster access.

87
00:05:55,625 --> 00:05:58,460
But the prompt is the source of truth.

88
00:05:58,460 --> 00:06:02,938
Real systems span multiple repos — an API,

89
00:06:02,991 --> 00:06:06,779
an SDK, a frontend, shared infrastructure.

90
00:06:08,998 --> 00:06:13,736
The AI dev environment gives you one workspace where the AI can

91
00:06:13,796 --> 00:06:16,219
run the whole system end to end.

92
00:06:17,560 --> 00:06:19,574
It's a container of containers.

93
00:06:20,494 --> 00:06:24,215
Each component runs in its own container,

94
00:06:24,575 --> 00:06:27,736
all inside one outer workspace.

95
00:06:29,395 --> 00:06:32,293
The Lead AI can start, stop,

96
00:06:32,383 --> 00:06:35,891
restart, and test any component from there.

97
00:06:37,392 --> 00:06:39,733
It runs locally or in the cloud.

98
00:06:40,493 --> 00:06:45,808
Cloud workspaces are useful for team handoff — another engineer

99
00:06:45,875 --> 00:06:49,009
picks up the same workspace and the same context.

100
00:06:50,988 --> 00:06:56,686
The environment includes Playwright for browser testing and Terraform for infrastructure.

101
00:06:57,865 --> 00:07:03,095
And there's an audit trail across all agent sessions — reproducibility,

102
00:07:03,162 --> 00:07:07,900
traceability, and evals for debugging agent behaviour.

103
00:07:08,035 --> 00:07:09,020
Here's how to start.

104
00:07:10,899 --> 00:07:14,463
Pick one repo and generate Progressive Disclosure docs for it.

105
00:07:15,223 --> 00:07:18,541
Any agent can then pick up that repo and work

106
00:07:18,610 --> 00:07:19,104
safely.

107
00:07:21,097 --> 00:07:25,256
Next, stand up one dev environment for a multi-repo system.

108
00:07:25,816 --> 00:07:28,773
The AI can run it end to end from day

109
00:07:28,853 --> 00:07:29,173
one.

110
00:07:30,752 --> 00:07:34,208
The docs and prompts are plain markdown — no plugins,

111
00:07:34,261 --> 00:07:35,249
no vendor lock-in.

112
00:07:37,146 --> 00:07:39,731
Start with one repo and one system,

113
00:07:39,771 --> 00:07:42,289
and you can use this operating model now.

